The '''Capra Grigia''', {{lang-fr|'''Chèvre grise des montagnes'''|italic=no}}, {{lang-de|'''Graue Bergziege'''|italic=no}},{{r|dad}} is a rare and endangered indigenous [[breed]] of [[goat|domestic goat]] from Switzerland. It originates in the valleys of the [[canton (administrative division)|cantons]] of the [[Grisons]] or Graubünden in the eastern part of the country, and of [[Ticino]] or Tessin in the south.{{r|szzv}} It is possibly related to the grey type of the [[Passeirer Gebirgsziege]] from the [[Autonomous Province of Bolzano]] in north-eastern Italy.{{r|save}}

==History==

Documentation of the Capra Grigia in the valleys of the Ticino and the Grisons goes back more than 100 years. Three regional types were distinguished: the Bleni-Valmaggia or Lavizzarer, the Liviner or Misoxer, and the Riveria.{{r|save}} The breed was not recognised in the reorganisation of Swiss goat breeds in 1938, and infection with [[caprine arthritis encephalitis]] in the mid-twentieth century contributed to its near-total disappearance.{{r|cgs}} The Swiss association [[ProSpecieRara]] launched a conservation and recovery project for the Capra Grigia in 1997, recorded all surviving members in a [[herd-book]], and started a controlled [[breeding programme]]. [[Breed standard]]s were formulated in 2005, and in 2006 the Capra Grigia was officially recognised as a Swiss breed.{{r|psr|page=112|cabi|page2=367}} In 2007 the total number registered was 190, and the [[conservation status]] was listed by the [[FAO]] as "critical-maintained".{{r|barb|cabi|page2=367}} In 2008, five apparently similar goats were discovered in the [[Valchiavenna]] in Italy, which increased the gene pool.{{r|psr}} In 2011 a breed association, Capra Grigia Schweiz, was formed.{{r|psr2}}

At the end of 2011 a population of 475–490 was reported to [[DAD-IS]].{{r|dad}}

== Characteristics ==

The Capra Grigia is sure-footed and agile, with hard hooves well-suited to the high mountain terrain of the southern Alps. The horns are strong, and grow upwards and outwards. The coat colour is similar to that of the Austrian {{ill|Blobe Ziege|de}}: it varies from a mottled dark grey to a pale silver-white; the legs are dark grey or black, and there is a dark [[dorsal stripe]].{{r|cabi|page=367}}

